Conduct a comprehensive benchmark comparison of the leading OpenAPI linting tools available as of 2025: Spectral (Stoplight), IBM API Linter (ibm-openapi-validator), Redocly CLI, and Vacuum. For each tool, research and report on the following dimensions:

Rule coverage: how many built-in rules does each tool ship with, how are rules categorized (structural correctness, security, documentation quality, design best practices), and what rule sets or profiles are available out of the box?

Performance characteristics: what is the typical validation latency for small specs (under 50 paths), medium specs (50-200 paths), and large specs (500+ paths)? Are there published benchmarks or community-reported numbers? Does each tool support streaming or incremental validation?

Extensibility model: how does each tool allow custom rules to be authored — JavaScript/TypeScript functions, Rego policies, YAML rule definitions, or other mechanisms? What is the learning curve and ecosystem maturity for custom rule development?

Integration ecosystem: which CI/CD platforms, editors (VS Code, JetBrains), API gateways, and design platforms natively integrate each tool? Is there a programmatic API (Node.js library, REST service) beyond the CLI?

False positive rates: are there any published studies, blog posts, or community forum discussions that compare false positive or false negative rates across these tools on real-world API specifications?

Governance use cases: how do organizations use these tools to enforce API design standards across teams — centralized rule repositories, versioned rulesets, spectral profiles shared via npm packages?

Conclude with a summary of which tool appears strongest in each dimension and what gaps exist in current open-source API linting tooling that represent opportunities for improvement.
